info.description: Yakitori is a Japanese dish of skewered chicken grilled over charcoal, typically seasoned with tare (a sweet soy glaze) or salt.
A popular yakitori item of grilled chicken skin, crispy and flavorful, typically seasoned with salt or tare.
Kokoro (chicken heart) is a common item in Japanese cuisine, especially in yakitori. It is typically skewered and grilled, offering a chewy texture and a rich, savory flavor.
Common Japanese offal item: chicken liver, often served grilled on skewers (yakitori) or used in various dishes; features a rich flavor and tender texture when cooked properly.
A Japanese dish likely featuring liver (kimo) from the back area, typically prepared by grilling or skewering in izakaya-style cuisine.
Seseri is chicken neck meat, a popular yakitori ingredient known for its tender texture and rich flavor, typically grilled on skewers with tare or salt.
A small-portion dish featuring harami (beef skirt steak) pieces, typically grilled or seared and served with sauces.

A traditional Japanese ingredient from older chickens, typically used in yakitori or simmered dishes; it offers a deeper, richer flavor compared to young chicken and is often grilled on skewers with tare or salt.
A classic Japanese yakitori dish featuring bite-sized chicken pieces skewered with green onions, typically grilled over charcoal and seasoned with tare sauce or salt.
Nankotsu refers to chicken cartilage, a popular ingredient in Japanese yakitori skewers. It is typically grilled until tender with a crunchy bite, and seasoned with salt or tare sauce.
Sasami is the chicken tenderloin, a lean and very tender cut from the chicken breast. It's commonly used in Japanese cuisine, often grilled or skewered, and enjoyed plain or with dipping sauces.
A popular Japanese-style appetizer made from chicken wings, typically seasoned and cooked by frying or grilling; commonly served in izakayas.
A term for uncommon or premium meat parts, typically prepared as specialty dishes or grilled to showcase their distinct flavor and texture.
A savory Japanese dish of grilled chicken gizzards (zuri) and engawa (the edge of a flounder eel) seasoned with black pepper.
info.text: ズリえんがわ黒胡椒焼き
info.text_translation: Gizzard and engawa grilled with black pepper.

info.description: Beef harami is a flavorful cut from the diaphragm (skirt area) of beef, commonly grilled in Japanese yakiniku and served with tare sauce, salt, or sesame oil.
info.text: 牛ハラミ キダング

info.description: A Japanese barbecue-style cut featuring fatty, marbled pork such as pork belly (buta bara) and pork toro, commonly grilled and enjoyed as skewers or in yakiniku.
A thin, classic sausage made from pork and/or beef, typically boiled, grilled, or fried and commonly served in hot dogs or sandwiches.
Two simple Japanese maki rolls, featuring shiso (perilla) leaf and tomato fillings, wrapped with sushi rice and nori.
info.text: しそ巻きとトマト巻き

info.description: A soft, white cheese with a mild flavor, commonly used on pizzas, in Caprese salads, and various Italian dishes.
A Japanese charcoal-grilled dish associated with the Yamaguchi region, typically featuring meat or seafood cooked over charcoal to impart a smoky, savory flavor.
Charcoal-grilled avocado, typically served as an appetizer or topping in Japanese cuisine, often lightly seasoned.
A simple Japanese ingredient pairing of white negi (green onion) and shiitake mushrooms, commonly used in soups, hot pots, or stir-fries.
A simple Japanese dish featuring mild shishito peppers and king oyster mushrooms, typically sautéed or grilled with garlic, soy sauce, and sesame.
info.text: ししとう エリンギ
info.text_translation: Shishito peppers and king oyster mushrooms

info.description: Garlic is a pungent bulb used as a staple seasoning in cuisines worldwide. It can be used fresh, minced, pressed, or roasted to add aroma and flavor to dishes.
A Japanese preparation of tataki using chicken thigh: thinly sliced pieces quickly seared on the outside while remaining juicy inside, typically served with ponzu or citrus-based sauce and garnishes.
A Japanese dish where chicken breast is lightly seared on the outside, then thinly sliced and served with dipping sauces such as ponzu or sesame.
A dish of thinly sliced chicken breast served as carpaccio, typically dressed with olive oil, lemon juice, salt and pepper, and often finished with greens or shaved cheese.
info.text: 鶏むね肉のカルパッチョ

info.description: Fresh tomato sliced into thin rounds, commonly used as a garnish or ingredient in salads, sandwiches, and various dishes.
A Japanese-style potato salad made with boiled potatoes, cucumber, carrot, and mayonnaise; a creamy side dish commonly served in Japanese cuisine.
A simple mixed-vegetable salad featuring fresh ingredients such as lettuce, cucumber, and tomatoes, lightly dressed to enhance the natural flavors.
A simple Italian pairing of ripe tomatoes and fresh mozzarella cheese, often served with basil, olive oil, and a pinch of salt.
info.text: トマトとモッツァレラチーズの

info.description: A classic Italian salad featuring fresh tomatoes, mozzarella, and basil, typically dressed with olive oil and a splash of balsamic vinegar.
Seseri Nanban is a Japanese dish featuring seseri (chicken neck meat) prepared in Nanban style—often fried or battered and tossed in a tangy vinegar-soy sauce, sometimes served with tartar sauce.
A Japanese dish of fried chicken gizzards prepared in nanban style, typically served with a sweet-sour vinegar sauce and often accompanied by onions or peppers.
A Japanese fried chicken dish featuring bonjiri, the tail meat of a chicken, typically marinated, seasoned, and deep-fried to crispy, flavorful bites.
A popular Japanese dish of bite-sized chicken thigh pieces, marinated in soy sauce, garlic, and ginger, lightly coated and deep-fried until crispy.
A Japanese fried dish made with seseri (chicken neck meat) coated in tempura batter and deep-fried until crisp, typically served with tentsuyu dipping sauce or a squeeze of lemon.
A tempura dish named after furisode, the formal long-sleeved kimono. It features light, crispy batter on seasonal vegetables or seafood, typically served with tentsuyu dipping sauce.
Atsu-age is a thick fried tofu common in Japanese cuisine; it has a crisp outer surface and a soft, sponge-like interior, often used in soups, stews, or served with soy sauce.
Fries are potatoes cut into sticks and deep-fried until golden and crispy, typically salted and served with ketchup or other dipping sauces.
Crispy baton-shaped sticks made from sweet potatoes, often fried or baked until golden; a popular snack or side dish.
info.text: サツマイモ スティック

info.description: A Japanese teppan-style dish featuring sliced mountain yam (yama-imo) cooked on a hot iron plate, usually with savory seasoning. It yields a crisp exterior with a creamy, starchy interior.
info.text_translation: Grilled mountain yam on a teppan

info.description: A Japanese-style dish where cheese is melted on a hot iron plate (teppan), often served as a savory appetizer or accompaniment with meat and vegetables.
Fresh mung bean sprouts, crisp and mildly sweet, widely used in Asian cuisines for stir-fries, soups, and salads.
Edamame are young soybeans boiled or steamed in salted water, often served warm as a snack or appetizer in Japanese cuisine.

A traditional Japanese sashimi-style dish of thinly sliced raw chicken served with wasabi, typically accompanied by soy sauce or ponzu for dipping and garnishes like green onion; commonly found in izakayas.
A Japanese dish of lightly crushed cucumber, often served as a refreshing side or salad, typically seasoned with salt, vinegar and sesame.
A soft, creamy dairy spread prepared in a Japanese-inspired style, commonly used as a spread on bread or crackers and as a base for fusion dishes.
A Japanese appetizer featuring chicken skin served with ponzu sauce; tangy citrus flavor and savory umami, commonly enjoyed as a yakitori-style dish.
A traditional Korean side dish (banchan) made with fermented napa cabbage, seasoned with chili pepper, garlic, ginger, and other spices. It is typically spicy, tangy, and crunchy.
A traditional Korean side dish made from fermented daikon radish, typically seasoned with chili pepper, garlic, and other aromatics, resulting in a crisp, tangy, and spicy flavor.
Chanja is a Korean side dish of spicy, salted fish entrails, typically made from pollock or other white fish, seasoned with chili peppers, garlic, sesame oil, and sesame seeds.
A Japanese snack of rice formed into a ball and grilled until lightly charred, often brushed with soy sauce or a savory glaze for extra flavor.
A traditional Japanese dish where hot tea, dashi, or broth is poured over cooked rice, often topped with ingredients such as pickles, grilled fish, seaweed, or sesame.
A donburi dish featuring skewered and grilled chicken served over steamed rice, typically brushed with tare sauce and garnished with sesame seeds and green onions.
A clear, light broth made by simmering chicken bones to extract rich flavor; commonly used as a base for soups, sauces, and hot dishes.
A platter of assorted fresh ingredients, typically featuring light, refreshing items such as vegetables and seafood, served as part of a cold appetizer course.
